54c71a73fbb1d5020b272cf4/c60e9/trim-shortcuts.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/6d8210a554c71a73fbb1d5020b272cf4/f06cd/trim-shortcuts.jpg 240w,\n/static/6d8210a554c71a73fbb1d5020b272cf4/a5e48/trim-shortcuts.jpg 480w,\n/static/6d8210a554c71a73fbb1d5020b272cf4/c60e9/trim-shortcuts.jpg 800w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>We already covered moving a cut with the U key, so that only leaves T and Y. T performs a slide edit by unjoining the end of the previous clip and the beginning of the next clip. A slide edit lets you move an entire clip through your timeline, adjusting the length of the clips on either side of it to compensate.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 766px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 36.25%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/svg+xml,%3csvg%20xmlns=\\'http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\'%20width=\\'400\\'%20height=\\'146\\'%20viewBox=\\'0%200%20400%20146\\'%20preserveAspectRatio=\\'none\\'%3e%3cpath%20d=\\'M0%2011v10h89v34H54c-28%200-34%200-33-1%200-2-2-4-6-4s-5%201-3%203h3l1-1%202-1c1%204%201%204-5%204-4%200-5%200-5-2%201-2%200-3-2-2v3c1%201%201%201-2%201-4%200-4%200-4%203v3h89v34c0%2030%200%2034-2%2034l-44%201H0v16h203v-16h-7l-8-1c0-1-1-2-4-2s-4%200-3%201l1%201h3c2%201-4%201-18%201l-21-1c-2-2-3-2-3%200h-2l1%202c1%201-10%201-25%201H91V63h26l27%201v5l1%205V61h58v-6h-15V33l-1%209c-1%209-1%209-5%209l-2%201c1%202%204%202%205%201h1c0%202-1%202-9%202s-9%200-9-2v-2l-1%202c0%202-1%202-11%202h-10l-1-18c0-15%200-18%201-17l29%201h28V0H0v11m209%200v10h99v34h-47a227%20227%200%2001-49-1c1%201%200%201-1%201-2%200-2%201-2%203v3h99v33l-1%2035-8%201-10%202h-4c1-2-4-2-38-2h-38v16h191v-16h-18V61h18v-6h-18V21h18V0H209v11m154%2024c0%2020%200%2020%2010%2020h8V21h-7l-9-1c-2-1-2-1-2%2015M91%2040v17h12l11-1v-3c2%200%202%201%202%202-1%202%200%202%208%202%207%200%208%200%207-1l-2-1h-2c0-1%202-2%205-2%204%200%205%200%205%202h-4l-1%201%204%201c2%200%203%200%202-2l1-3%201%201c0%203%200%204%202%204l1-9%201-17v-8H91v17m219%200v17h52V23h-52v17m53%2035a106%20106%200%20001%2021v31c1%203%201%203%209%203h8V61h-8l-9-1c-1-1-1%203-1%2015m-53%2023v34h26c15%200%2026%200%2025-1l-1-2h1c1%201%201-4%201-15l-1-17-1-2c0-2%200-2%201%200%201%201%201-5%201-15V63h-52v35\\'%20fill=\\'%23d3d3d3\\'%20fill-rule=\\'evenodd\\'/%3e%3c/svg%3e'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"slide edit\"\n        title=\"slide edit\"\n        src=\"/static/19da33146e9828335623c87060898b42/8dbf5/Selection_016.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/19da33146e9828335623c87060898b42/58794/Selection_016.png 240w,\n/static/19da33146e9828335623c87060898b42/3166f/Selection_016.png 480w,\n/static/19da33146e9828335623c87060898b42/8dbf5/Selection_016.png 766w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 766px) 100vw, 766px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>The Y key initiates a slip edit by unjoining the beginning and end of the current clip. Slip edits allow you to change the in and out point of a clip without modifying its length. It’s a little confusing the first time you do it, so imagine a strip of film being passed beneath a small window. The edges of the window are your in and out points. A slip edit rolls the film by, changing what appears within the window but not the size or position of the window. That may have been equally confusing, if so please disregard.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 589px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 47.91666666666667%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/svg+xml,%3csvg%20xmlns=\\'http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\'%20width=\\'400\\'%20height=\\'192\\'%20viewBox=\\'0%200%20400%20192\\'%20preserveAspectRatio=\\'none\\'%3e%3cpath%20d=\\'M0%2014v13h24l25%201v44H0v7h25l24%201v89H0v23h196v-23h-19v-14c0-17-1-18-2-3%200%2012%200%2011-3%2011l-3%201-2-1c-2-2-2-2-3-1l-2%201-1%202-1-1-2-3-1%203c-2%203-2%203%200%203h2c3%201%206%201%207-1l1-1c0%203%202%203%203%201l1-1%202%203c2%201-8%201-25%201h-28V79h76v-7h-19V53c0-18%200-18-1-7a594%20594%200%2000-3%2020h-3l-1%201h-3l-1-1v-2l-1%201-1%201-2%202-1-1c-1-4-2-4-4%200-1%203-1%203%201%203h6v-3l1%202c0%202%202%201%202-1l1%201%202%203%201-3%201-1c0%202%201%202%203%201h1l-1%201v1c1%201-8%201-26%201h-28V27h76V0H0v14m203%200v13h66v45h-66v7h66v90h-66v23h197v-11c0-11%200-12-2-12s-2-1-2-45%200-45%202-45%202-1%202-3c0-3%200-4-2-4s-2-1-2-22c0-22%200-23%202-23s2-1%202-13V0H203v14m136%2028l1%2023v7h28c18%200%2027%200%2025-1-3-1-3-6%200-5%202%200%202-2%202-20V27h-56v15M51%2050l1%2023c2%201%2061%202%2064%200%202%200%202-2%202-22V30H86l-33-1c-2-1-2%200-2%2021m220%200c0%2019%200%2023%202%2023h63l1-22V30h-31l-32-1c-3-2-3%200-3%2021m69%2030v89h28c15%200%2027%200%2026-1l-1-1c1-1%201-1%200%200l-2-2%202-2c3%200%203-40%200-40l1-1c1-1%201-1-1-1-1%201-2%200-2-1l2-2c2%200%202-1%202-19V79h-27l-28%201M51%20124v45l2%201c3%203%2061%203%2063%201%202-1%202-3%202-14l1-13v-2l-1-21a112%20112%200%20011-24l-1-8v-7H86l-33-1c-2-1-2%202-2%2043m220%201v45l3%201c3%202%2059%201%2061%200s2-18%202-81v-8h-31l-33-1c-2-1-2-1-2%2044m-95-27l-1%2020h-3l-3%201-2-1-2-2-2%202c-3%203-3%203-3%201-1-3-3-2-4%201l-1%203h5c5%200%205-1%205-3%200-3%201-3%202%201%201%202%201%202%202%201l2-1%202%202%203%202c1%201%201-3%201-14V96l-1%202\\'%20fill=\\'%23d3d3d3\\'%20fill-rule=\\'evenodd\\'/%3e%3c/svg%3e'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"slip edit\"\n        title=\"slip edit\"\n        src=\"/static/30808dc30d39fa3e29301dcacd2e3a72/c1f25/Selection_020.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/30808dc30d39fa3e29301dcacd2e3a72/58794/Selection_020.png 240w,\n/static/30808dc30d39fa3e29301dcacd2e3a72/3166f/Selection_020.png 480w,\n/static/30808dc30d39fa3e29301dcacd2e3a72/c1f25/Selection_020.png 589w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 589px) 100vw, 589px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>With these trimming tools, you are well prepared to finish a fine cut of your edit. Every editor must develop their own style, so I won’t tell you how to work your magic, but I will give you a few suggestions.</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Match actions:</strong> You can “hide” an edit by cutting in the middle of an action, such as a head turning or a fist landing its mark on a face. The easiest way to time this properly is to line up the edit on the end of the action, then roll the cut backward several frames.</li>\n<li><strong>Watch the eyes:</strong> Let your character’s eyes direct your cutting. If you are trying to cut away from a character, look for movement in her eyes. If she turns to look at something, cut away as soon as she has locked eyes with her target. Even cutting on subtle eye movements can make your film less jarring.</li>\n<li><strong>Know when to hold a shot:</strong> Don’t get overzealous with your cutting. Sometimes we learn more about a character by watching how he reacts to his partner.</li>\n<li><strong>Be ruthless:</strong> Trim, trim, trim. The tighter edit is, the better it flows. Can you trim a few frames here? One frame there? Every single frame counts.</li>\n<li><strong>Don’t get too attached:</strong> Never be afraid to cut bits that you love if it improves the overall project.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Most importantly, have fun! There’s no shame in scrubbing the playhead back and forth to make your actors dance. I do it all the time.</p>","excerpt":"If you followed the basic timeline editing tutorial, you should now have a very rough assemblage of clips on your Lightworks timeline. When…","frontmatter":{"title":"Lightworks Video Editing: Advanced Trimming Techniques","author":"Jay Nielsen","category":"tutorial","image":{"childImageSharp":{"fluid":{"tracedSVG":"data:image/svg+xml,%3csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20width='400'%20height='263'%20viewBox='0%200%20400%20263'%20preserveAspectRatio='none'%3e%3cpath%20d='M19%209h-9v40L9%2084l-1-5v6c0%205%200%206-2%206-1%200-2%200-2%203-1%204-2%205-2%202l-1-3-1%2085v85h401v-86c0-47-1-67-1-45v40l-3-1-3%201-1%202c-2%200-2-14-2-88l-1-76A9552%209552%200%200074%209H19m-5%2053a399%20399%200%20002%2036l4%203c4%201%205%202%203%203-3%201%200%203%204%203s13%203%2013%204l6%201c6%200%206%200%207%204v4a1391%201391%200%2000125%202h17V20H14v42m183-41a1003%201003%200%20003%2076l2%204%202%204c0%202%202%204%2010%205l6%202c1%202%201%202%2010-3%202-1%203-1%202%203%200%203-1%204-5%205l-6%203c-1%202%200%202%2056%202a269%20269%200%200086-6l5-1h6l2-1%201-47V20h-90l-90%201m-75%2017c-6%202-28%2015-28%2017h3c2-1%203-1%202%201l3%206c3%203%204%204%2012%204%2020%201%2015%202-8%202a280%20280%200%2000-40%202c0%202%205%202%2013%201s18%200%2018%202l-4%203c-6%203-3%204%207%201l34-6c4%201-21%2010-28%2010-9%201-14%202-13%203l-1%203c-1%201-1%201%201%201%209-3%2025-1%2023%203-4%2010-5%2016-2%209%203-5%205-6%207-3%205%204%2010%204%2023%202l12-2%201%207%202%207V86c1-10-1-17-8-27a763%20763%200%2001-14-20c-3-2-12-2-15-1m168%205h-8v10c0%2012%201%2017%203%2017l5%201h7c5-3%209-3%2014-1%2011%204%2022-12%2015-22l-2-4c0-2-9-2-34-1m-171%206c-4%204%200%2011%206%2011s8-6%203-10c-4-4-6-4-9-1m201%201a88%2088%200%2001-8%202c-2%200-1%2010%201%2011%203%202%206%203%206%201l-1-1c-2%200%202-3%204-3v2h1c2-3%203-11%201-12h-4m-26%203c-3%200-4%201-4%203l-2%202-1%202c0%202%20